'''Neuroleadership''' refers to the application of findings from [[neuroscience]] to the field of [[leadership]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb6698/is_3_75/ai_n56939147/ | title=NeuroLeadership: sustaining research relevance into the 21st century | publisher=SAM Advanced Management Journal | date=June 22, 2010 | accessdate=March 30, 2012 |author1=Lafferty, Christina L. |author2=Alford, Kenneth L. }}</ref> The term neuroleadership was first coined by David Rock in 2006 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://davidrock.net/ |title=David Rock |publisher=David Rock |date=2011-11-06 |accessdate=2012-03-31}}</ref> in the US publication [[Strategy+Business]].<ref>[http://www.strategy-business.com/press/freearticle/06207 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071114173817/http://www.strategy-business.com/press/freearticle/06207 |date=November 14, 2007 }}</ref> In 2009 Mark Waldman developed a NeuroLeadership class that is part of the Executive MBA program at Loyola Marymount University. Neuroleadership claims to bring neuroscientific knowledge into the areas of [[leadership development]], [[management]] training, change management, education, consulting and coaching. One of the major components of the NeuroLeadership programs being introduced in universities and organizations is the concept of mindfulness, an outgrowth of the work originally established by Jon Kabat Zinn. 

==Criticism==
Neuroleadership is not without its critics.<ref>See for example comments by Howard Gardner and Warren Bennis in [http://www.afraccess.com/Index_mxml.html?URL=EDP:%2f%2f20071108000019927746 Australian Financial Review 9 November 2007]</ref> They question whether having scientific brain data to back up what was commonly believed adds any value.

